Note that Frnace has serious legal restrictions on the use
of cryptography.  (see below)


	WASHINGTON (UPI) -- The CIA has warned more than 70 U.S. defense,
aerospace and financial firms their industrial secrets are targets of
French intelligence agents and diplomats.
	The warning led Hughes Aircraft Co. to drop plans to exhibit
aerospace equipment at the Paris Air Show in June, according to
published reports.
	A 21-page French government document from about 1990 outlines U.S.
aerospace and defense corporate secrets in which French companies are
interested, U.S. industry officials said.
	Defense Week said Monday the memo targets 49 companies and 24
financial institutions in the U.S.
	The unsigned, undated document, in French and stamped ``Defense
Confidential,'' said French diplomats in the U.S. should focus on
research work, marketing strategies and U.S. positions in trade
disputes, the Washington Post said Tuesday.
	Hughes officials said they were told one item the French memo lists
is Hughes' HS601 communications satellite. French firms recently outbid
Hughes to provide $258 million in communications spacecraft to Arab
countries.
	A French embassy spokesman told the Washington Post, ``There is
nothing in this document to indicate that it was released by French
government offices.''
	Japan also has tried to obtain U.S. industrial secrets, government
officials have said.
	U.S. intelligence agencies long have privately told U.S. business
executives on trips to France and some other allied nations to closely
guard their firms' secrets while abroad.
	The debate over whether the CIA and other intelligence agencies
should practice industrial espionage for U.S. firms ``is the hottest
current topic in intelligence policy,'' CIA Director R. James Woolsey
said during his confirmation hearings. His predecessor, Robert Gates,
opposed the practice.
	Industry specialists and intelligence experts maintain the practice
is full of foreign policy and legal difficulties.
	A CIA official told the Washington Post the agency's sharing of the
French memo is a continuation of tipping U.S. firms when the government
learns of attempts at industrial espionage.
	The London Sunday Times said April 11 the French memo included
information about the private life of then-President George Bush. U.S.
authorities responded by tightening security procedures for government
officials, the paper said.




-----------------end of UPI article-----------------
